Oscars 2013: Use these tricks to find out who will (possibly) win at the Oscars
Telegraph film critic Robbie Collin explains how to predict who will be the winners at this year's Oscars. The true soundtrack to the Oscars is the music of critics arguing Photo: GETTY	By Robbie Collin
7:00AM GMT 23 Feb 2013
Follow Comments
Imagine there exists a group of film industry insiders who have correctly predicted the winners of the Best Picture Academy Award nine times in the past decade. Now imagine that this same shadowy cabal publishes its prediction very year, almost a month before Oscar night. Well, you don’t actually have to imagine this at all, because it’s true. With their Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Motion Pictures award, the Directors Guild of America has been quietly pre-ordaining the Best Picture Oscar since 1948 with uncanny accuracy. The DGA – a professional body made up of 14,500 film and television directors working in the US – has given its annual film prize to the eventual Best Picture winner 50 times in 63 years. What’s more, the same award has tallied with the Best Director Oscar 57 times, and is in the middle of an unbroken nine-year success streak. And now what if I was to tell you that in addition to this, there is a simple gimmick that can rule out at least half of the Best Picture nominees at a stroke, and which has only failed once since the earliest days of the Oscar ceremony? Again, this occult rubric actually exists: it is called the Best Director nominees list. Since 1933, the only film to have won the Academy’s top honour without also being mentioned in the directing category is Driving Miss Daisy. Otherwise, in almost eight decades of screenings, campaigns and secret ballots, the link has stayed unbroken. Related Articles
Oscars host Seth MacFarlane: can he save the Awards?
24 Feb 2013
Argo prompts most expensive Oscar campaigns ever
20 Feb 2013
Does Adele's Skyfall deserve to win an Oscar?
21 Feb 2013
Oscars 2013: Les Miserables shouldn't win an Oscar
22 Feb 2013
Abraham Lincoln on screen
21 Feb 2013
Oscars 2013: feast fit for stars and vegans
23 Jan 2013
Before you take the deeds to your house to the nearest branch of Betfred, though, I should warn you that this year, these bellwethers are pointing in opposite directions, so whatever happens at tomorrow night’s ceremony, at least one of them will look a little less reliable in future. According to the nominations rule, Ben Affleck’s widely praised thriller Argo has no chance at Best Picture, because Affleck was not shortlisted in the Best Director category by the Academy’s 200-strong directors’ branch. On the strength of its DGA award, however, Argo’s Best Picture victory should be a certainty. But this is all part of the fun of the Oscar predictions racket, where money and reputations are staked – and lost – on forecasting the fickle tastes of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences’s 5,783 members. Earlier this week, the film industry’s trade paper, The Hollywood Reporter, interviewed a director marking their ballot, allowing its readers an insight into the grapplings of the average Oscar voter. Michael Haneke’s Amour, a Palme d’Or winner at Cannes, was dismissed as “just a woman dying, and there’s no real story”. A Royal Affair, the Danish contender in the Best Foreign Language category, was passed over because “I fell asleep as I was watching it”. Life of Pi was also given short shrift: “Very well-directed and extremely well-thought-out, but I was put off by the religious message at the end,” said the director, who perhaps wisely elected to remain anonymous. Michael Haneke's Amour
Even for Academy members, second-guessing their colleagues is a slippery business. Listen on YouTube to the collective roar of disbelief that followed Jack Nicholson’s 2005 announcement that the Best Picture winner was not Ang Lee’s critically acclaimed gay cowboy romance Brokeback Mountain, but the Paul Haggis anti-racism drama Crash. Yet for those able to read the portents, Crash’s “surprise” victory was not so much of a surprise at all. Hollywood may like to think of itself as a liberal place, but it is not quite gay-cowboy-liberal just yet, and Tony Curtis and Ernest Borgnine, high-profile Academy members the pair, both publicly denounced Brokeback Mountain in the weeks leading up to the 2005 ceremony. (“If John Wayne were alive, he’d be rolling over in his grave,” Borgnine said.) A vote for Crash, with its less contentious message that racism isn’t very nice, allowed members to feel like they were still doing their bit. Consider this year’s contenders with that mindset, and the picture becomes clearer. Zero Dark Thirty, with its controversial depictions of present-day political strife in the Middle East, has generated less positive buzz than Argo, with its nostalgic depictions of Middle-Eastern political strife of yesteryear. Jessica Chastain in Zero Dark Thirty
It also goes some way to explain why Django Unchained, Quentin Tarantino’s splashily violent anti-slavery Western, is languishing in the shadow of Steven Spielberg’s stately anti-slavery period drama Lincoln. Blood and guts has always been hard for the Academy to stomach: think back to the 1981 ceremony, when Martin Scorsese’s Raging Bull was overshadowed by Robert Redford’s Ordinary People. Fast-forward 10 years and Scorsese’s Goodfellas was trumped by Kevin Costner’s Dances with Wolves. Emotional violence is fine so long as it is neatly resolved, but without a tidy ending you’re scuppered. Hence no Best Picture nomination this year for Paul Thomas Anderson’s troublingly open-ended melodrama The Master, or for other morally cloudy films in the past that are often ranked among the greatest ever made: Robert Altman’s Short Cuts, Stanley Kubrick’s 2001: A Space Odyssey, Alfred Hitchcock’s Vertigo, John Ford’s The Searchers, Carol Reed’s The Third Man. A final, crucial factor is the Academy’s ongoing efforts to make the Oscars more relevant to younger audiences. That was the rationale behind increasing the number of Best Picture nominees three years ago, and perhaps has steered their Best Picture choices over the past few years: The Artist, The King’s Speech, The Hurt Locker, Slumdog Millionaire and No Country for Old Men. A victory for Argo tomorrow night seems like a done deal. Is it the year’s best picture? Of course not. But is it a Best Picture? Almost inevitably. Follow Telegraph Film on Twitter
Robbie Collin, chief film critic
