What, for instance, was Theresa May up to when she suddenly proposed powers to strip foreign-born terror suspects of British citizenship? I have been generally supportive of the counter-terrorist measures proposed since 9/11 by Labour and Tory home secretaries alike: it is folly to pretend, as so many do, that a new conflict can be fought with old tools. That said, such measures should never be taken lightly. What Mrs May proposed last week has been eclipsed by the Raab amendment and its aftermath. But it is a significant step, and one that deserves detailed reflection. If passed into law, it will certainly leave some individuals stateless and, as a consequence, conspicuously vulnerable to ill-treatment and torture.
I am told, somewhat elliptically, that her 11th-hour amendment reflected fresh information about the number of terrorist suspects in this country and their possible purpose. Very well: let this contingency be discussed, as far as national security allows. Instead, the measure was swallowed by the petty politics of rebellion and barely scrutinised. This is not statesmanship.
Inadvertently, the Immigration Bill, which will now proceed to the Upper House, has become a political parable of the electoral struggle ahead. It embodies both Cameron’s desire to trump the UK Independence Party and – strategically – his insistence that he would go much further, were he at the helm of a purely Conservative government rather than a bipartisan Coalition.
It is true that, with a decent Tory majority, the PM would probably have taken tougher measures on immigration, sooner in the Parliament. Welfare reform, the Human Rights Act, taxation, free schools: in all these areas of policy and others it is at least plausible that a fully-Conservative government would have acted differently, and more radically.
Yet there is deep peril embedded in this narrative. First, it risks restoring the entirely discredited notion that the reason the Conservatives fell short in 2010 is that they were not sufficiently Right-wing: a proposition for which there is precisely zero evidence. Second, the relentless portrayal of Clegg as a contaminant in the Tory pool creates a potential crisis of expectation. Often, when Conservatives say “…if only the Lib Dems weren’t so fussy” what they really mean is “if only our international treaty obligations were different” or “if only we didn’t have to live in the reality-based community”.
It is not, for instance, Nick Clegg’s fault that Article 8 of the ECHR says what it does about family life or that Britain signed the convention (having drafted it) 64 years ago. Yes, a Tory-only government might indeed tear up that commitment or at least suspend it. But let us not pretend that such an act would be straightforward politically or constitutionally, requiring only the absence of the Lib Dems from the Cabinet table.
The same logic applies to welfare reform. Its progress has often been framed as a battle between tough Tories and lily-livered Lib Dems. But – again – the reality is much more subtle. Often, the very Conservatives who argue most vociferously for welfare cuts as a generality are the most plaintive about their surgeries, full of constituents complaining about the “bedroom tax” or relatives in wheelchairs mysteriously judged fit to work by Atos. These human dilemmas were not invented by the Lib Dems and will not evaporate if, as is now at least conceivable, the Conservatives win the next election outright.
The great achievement of Cameron’s predecessor as Tory leader, Michael Howard, was to restore the order that had been conspicuously lacking in the party’s ranks since the early Nineties. Last week, he made a rare intervention to remind his colleagues that “what is needed in this stage of the parliament is a degree of self-discipline by Conservative backbenchers”. In other words, unite or die.
Lord Howard is right. But unity is more than self-discipline; it is a collective response to authority. Cameron’s horizons are brightening, but he was wrong last week to avoid confrontation with his backbenchers. Too often, Tory dissenters and their sympathisers brandish the claims of conscience like Cambridge spies. It is not the primary function of a prime minister to make MPs feel good. A functioning democracy needs those who will speak truth to power. But it also needs leaders brave enough to speak truth to dissent.
